@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Main"
@{u}What is it?@{uu}

Postscript fonts have been very popular in the last few years. Most text processors can use this type of outline font and many users have access to a huge library of high quality postscript fonts.

The bad news is that there's a very popular other computer system that's so old fashioned that it still uses filenames consisting of a basename of 8 letters and a 3 letter @{"extension" link "Extensions" 0}. You could think that that's enough, but all chars used in the filenames of this computer system are uppercase.

So what has this got to do with me? Well, people using the so called 'other computer system' are a good source for postscript fonts. But when you're copying postscript fonts from this kind of people to the AMIGA world you'll see that the filenames of the fonts are almost as stupid as they could be:

'AB______@{".PFB" link "Extensions" 0}' - guess what's the @{u}real@{uu} name of this font!

The inventors of Postscript must have thought about the 'other computer system' and embedded the @{b}real@{ub} name of the font in the font file itself. And this is what @{b}PsRename@{ub} does - it takes a bunch of silly named postscript fonts (currently only the most used pfb format is processed) and gives them with human readable names.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "Copyright"
@prev "Introduction"
@{u}Usage@{uu}

@{b}PsRename@{ub} needs OS 2.0 or later to run.

@{b}PsRename@{ub} must be used from Shell. It's command line template is:

@{i}PsRename FROM/A,ALL/S,SIMULATE=SIM/S,NOEXTENSION=NE/S,QUIET/S@{ui}

@{u}FROM@{uu}

@{b}FROM@{ub} specifies the pattern, file or directory where @{b}PsRename@{ub} will work. All AmigaDOS 2.0 patterns are allowed. @{b}PsRename@{ub} (hopefully) won't crash when you're feeding it with something else than @{"PFB" link "Extensions" 0} files, but it isn't that good either. Best is to use a pattern like '#?@{".pfb" link "Extensions" 0}' if your font files all end with the extension '@{".pfb" link "Extensions" 0}'.

@{u}ALL@{uu}

@{b}ALL@{ub} tells @{b}PsRename@{ub} that it should recursively scan down all subdirectories that it hits when scanning for postscript fonts. This is very useful if your fonts are spread in many directories.

@{u}SIMULATE@{uu}

@{b}SIMULATE@{ub} is a switch that forces @{b}PsRename@{ub} to only simulate the renaming. This means that the files won't be renamed, @{b}PsRename@{ub} only shows you what it wants to do. Then you can decide whether you want it like that or not.

@{u}NOEXTENSION@{uu}

@{b}NOEXTENSION@{ub} will disable @{b}PsRename@{ub} to append the '@{".pfb" link "Extensions" 0}' extension. It is a matter of taste if you like extensions or if you need them.

@{u}QUIET@{uu}

@{b}QUIET@{ub} will disable most text output done by @{b}PsRename@{ub}.

@endnode

